from Middle English <i>gode</i> ‘good’ (Old English <i>gōd</i>).","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Gode</i>, representing either Old English <i>Goda</i> (male) or <i>Gode</i> (female), in part a byname and in part a short form of various compound names with the first element <i>gōd</i>, or perhaps a pet form of Old French names in <i>God-</i> such as   Godfrey  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Gut   and   Guth  , or Dutch <b>Goed</b> and   Goede  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Goode was born in 1250, in Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom as the son of Richard Goode. He married Mrs Goode in 1280, in Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1291, in his hometown, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1250–1291":"1250–1291","1254–1284":"1254–1284","1281–Male":"1281–Surnud","1221–Male":"1221–Surnud","1221":"1221","1254":"1254","1284":"1284","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1291":"1291","Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whitstone,Cornwall,England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whitstone, Cornwall, England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1250–1291":"1250–1291","1254–1284":"1254–1284","1281–Male":"1281–Kuollut","1221–Male":"1221–Kuollut","1221":"1221","1254":"1254","1284":"1284","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1291":"1291","Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Whitstone,Cornwall,England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Whitstone, Cornwall, England":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1250–1291":"1250–1291","1254–1284":"1254–1284","1281–Male":"1281–Décédé","1221–Male":"1221–Décédé","1221":"1221","1254":"1254","1284":"1284","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1291":"1291","Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Whitstone, Cornouailles, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Whitstone,Cornwall,England":"Whitstone, Cornouailles, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Whitstone, Cornwall, England":"Whitstone, Cornouailles, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Cornwall, England":"Cornouailles, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Richard Goode est né en 1250, à Whitstone, Co